---
import Layout from '../../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import SiteHeader from '../../../components/SiteHeader.astro';
import MadeByKaj from '../../../components/MadeByKaj.astro';

const basePath = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---

<Layout
	title="3I/ATLAS at parsec scale | Learn | Found in Space"
	description="Plot the inbound and outbound interstellar rays of 3I/ATLAS to see how an interstellar comet crosses the solar neighbourhood."
>
	<SiteHeader section="Learn" />

	<main class="page atlas-page">
		<section class="hero atlas-intro">
			<nav class="breadcrumb" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
				<a href={`${basePath}learn/`}>Learn</a>
				<span class="breadcrumb__sep" aria-hidden="true">›</span>
				<span>3I/ATLAS at parsec scale</span>
			</nav>
			<p class="eyebrow">Interstellar visitor</p>
			<h1>3I/ATLAS at parsec scale</h1>
			<p class="lede">
				Treat the comet as two straight interstellar rays: a blue inbound branch arriving at the
				Sun, and a gold outbound branch leaving in a slightly different direction. At this
				scale, the entire solar-system passage collapses into one small kink in the line. Here
				the rays are extended to 1 kiloparsec so the geometry reads as a genuinely large
				interstellar track through the local galaxy.
			</p>
		</section>

		<section class="prose atlas-body">
			<h2>Two asymptotes, one solar-system pass</h2>
			<p>
				This first view deliberately ignores the AU-scale details. The perihelion distance in
				the current orbit solution is only 1.35648 au, which is effectively zero on a plot
				measured in parsecs. That makes the right first lesson a geometric one: where
				3I/ATLAS came from, where it is going, and how slightly those two directions differ.
			</p>
			<p>
				The two branches are not mirrors. The outbound line has been nudged by the comet's
				planetary encounter geometry, with Jupiter providing the dominant perturbation around
				March 16, 2026. The bend is tiny, but on a clean 3D plot it is real and visible.
			</p>
			<p>
				The dotted markers along both rays are spaced at 100,000-year intervals. At roughly
				58 kilometres per second, 3I/ATLAS covers about 5.93 parsecs in one hundred millennia,
				which keeps the timing marks visually separated even when the full rays run out to
				1 kiloparsec.
			</p>
		</section>

		<div class="narrated-tour" data-three-i-atlas-tour>
			<div class="narrated-tour__chapters">
				<section class="narrated-tour__chapter" data-view="inbound">
					<p class="narrated-tour__chapter-eyebrow">Inbound branch · looking sunward</p>
					<h2 class="narrated-tour__chapter-title">Approaching from interstellar space</h2>
					<p>
						Start several parsecs out on the inbound axis and look toward the Sun. The blue
						ray marks the comet's incoming asymptote: at this scale, 3I/ATLAS is almost
						perfectly a straight line aimed at the inner solar system.
					</p>
					<p>
						The Sun marks the point where the parsec-scale simplification breaks down. In
						reality the comet misses the Sun by over an astronomical unit, but that gap is so
						small compared with a parsec that it vanishes on this plot.
					</p>
				</section>

				<section class="narrated-tour__chapter" data-view="outbound">
					<p class="narrated-tour__chapter-eyebrow">Outbound branch · looking back home</p>
					<h2 class="narrated-tour__chapter-title">The exit direction is not the same</h2>
					<p>
						Jump to the outbound side and look back at the Sun. The gold ray shows where the
						comet is heading after it leaves the planetary system. It is close to the inbound
						direction, but not identical.
					</p>
					<p>
						That mismatch is the whole point of plotting two lines instead of one. It encodes
						the deflection caused by the inner-solar-system encounter, dominated by Jupiter
						rather than by a simple mirror reflection at the Sun.
					</p>
				</section>

				<section class="narrated-tour__chapter" data-view="three-d">
					<p class="narrated-tour__chapter-eyebrow">Orbiting view · full geometry</p>
					<h2 class="narrated-tour__chapter-title">Seen in 3D, the bend appears</h2>
					<p>
						Pull back and orbit the system. The two rays meet at the Sun and form a shallow
						angle in three dimensions. This is the parsec-scale picture the proposal is really
						about: an interstellar object crossing our neighbourhood, not a comet sketch in
						the planetary plane.
					</p>
					<p>
						The next step from here would be to walk backward along the inbound ray and ask
						which nearby stars the comet passed closest to before it reached the Sun. That is
						a separate problem, but this viewer gives us the right starting geometry.
					</p>
				</section>

				<section class="narrated-tour__chapter" data-view="free-roam">
					<p class="narrated-tour__chapter-eyebrow">Final state · manual exploration</p>
					<h2 class="narrated-tour__chapter-title">Take over and explore the full 1 kpc rays</h2>
					<p>
						The guided tour ends here. Once this view settles, the camera unlocks and you can
						explore manually to inspect the full 1 kiloparsec inbound and outbound lines from whatever
						angle feels most useful.
					</p>
					<p>
						On desktop, drag to look around and use the movement keys to roam through the
						scene. This is the right place to start asking the next question: what lies close
						to the inbound path if we trace the comet backward through the local stars?
					</p>
				</section>

				<div class="narrated-tour__spacer" aria-hidden="true"></div>
			</div>

			<div class="narrated-tour__viewer-col">
				<div class="narrated-tour__viewer-sticky">
					<div class="narrated-tour__nav">
						<button type="button" class="narrated-tour__nav-button" data-view-fly="inbound">Inbound</button>
						<button type="button" class="narrated-tour__nav-button" data-view-fly="outbound">Outbound</button>
						<button type="button" class="narrated-tour__nav-button" data-view-fly="three-d">3D view</button>
						<button type="button" class="narrated-tour__nav-button" data-view-fly="free-roam">Free roam</button>
					</div>
					<div class="narrated-tour__viewer-shell" data-three-i-atlas-shell></div>
					<span class="narrated-tour__status" data-three-i-atlas-status>Loading...</span>
				</div>
			</div>
		</div>

		<section class="section-grid atlas-notes">
			<article class="panel">
				<p class="panel__eyebrow">Why this works</p>
				<h3>Parsec scale erases the miss distance</h3>
				<p>
					A perihelion of 1.35648 au is about 6.6 × 10<sup>-6</sup> parsecs. On a diagram that
					spans many parsecs, the comet's solar-system flyby is visually indistinguishable from
					a line that passes through the Sun.
				</p>
			</article>

			<article class="panel">
				<p class="panel__eyebrow">Velocity</p>
				<h3>About 58 km/s means 5.93 pc per 100,000 years</h3>
				<p>
					The inbound solution is about 57.995 km/s and the outbound one about 58.010 km/s.
					That is why the markers now sit much farther apart: each dot marks roughly
					six parsecs of travel, which is long enough to read clearly at this scale.
				</p>
			</article>

			<article class="panel">
				<p class="panel__eyebrow">What comes next</p>
				<h3>Trace the inbound branch backward</h3>
				<p>
					Once the geometry is in place, the fun next question is historical: which nearby
					stars sit closest to the inbound line, and are any of those approaches close enough
					to be dynamically interesting?
				</p>
			</article>

			<article class="panel panel--accent panel--wide atlas-follow-up">
				<p class="panel__eyebrow">Future layer</p>
				<h3>Add the AU-scale inner solar system separately</h3>
				<p>
					The cleanest next step is not to force a single viewer to do everything. Keep this
					parsec-scale tour for the interstellar geometry, then add a second layer or inset for
					the heliocentric orbit and the Jupiter encounter itself.
				</p>
			</article>
		</section>

		<MadeByKaj />
	</main>
</Layout>

<script>
	import { mountThreeIAtlasViewer } from '../../../scripts/three-i-atlas-viewer.js';
	import { setupNarratedTour } from '../../../scripts/narrated-tour.js';

	const tourRoot = document.querySelector('[data-three-i-atlas-tour]');
	const mount = document.querySelector('[data-three-i-atlas-shell]');
	const statusEl = document.querySelector('[data-three-i-atlas-status]');
	const chapters = tourRoot?.querySelectorAll('.narrated-tour__chapter[data-view]') ?? [];
	const navButtons = tourRoot?.querySelectorAll('[data-view-fly]') ?? [];

	if (mount && tourRoot) {
		mountThreeIAtlasViewer(mount, {
			onStatus(msg) {
				if (statusEl) statusEl.textContent = msg;
			},
		}).then((result) => {
			setupNarratedTour({
				root: tourRoot,
				chapters,
				navButtons,
				getChapterId(chapter) {
					return chapter.dataset.view;
				},
				getNavButtonId(button) {
					return button.dataset.viewFly;
				},
				activate(id) {
					result.goTo(id);
				},
				statusEl,
				initialId: 'inbound',
				desktopStatus: 'Scroll the story or use the pills to change viewpoint. In the final chapter, drag to look and use the keyboard to roam.',
				phoneStatus: 'Scroll the story to change viewpoint.',
			});
		}).catch((err) => {
			console.error('[website:three-i-atlas]', err);
			if (statusEl) statusEl.textContent = err instanceof Error ? err.message : String(err);
		});
	}
</script>

<style>
	.atlas-intro,
	.atlas-body,
	.atlas-notes {
		max-width: 48rem;
	}

	.atlas-page h1 {
		margin: 0;
		max-width: 12ch;
		font-size: clamp(2.4rem, 6vw, 4.2rem);
		line-height: 1.02;
		font-weight: 600;
		letter-spacing: -0.03em;
	}

	.atlas-body {
		padding-bottom: 1rem;
	}

	.atlas-notes {
		grid-template-columns: repeat(2, minmax(0, 1fr));
	}

	.atlas-notes h3 {
		margin: 0 0 0.65rem;
		font-size: 1.28rem;
		line-height: 1.15;
		color: var(--fis-text);
	}

	.atlas-notes p {
		margin: 0;
		line-height: 1.72;
		color: var(--fis-text-soft);
	}

	@media (max-width: 900px) {
		.atlas-notes {
			grid-template-columns: 1fr;
		}
	}
</style>
